04565nam a22005415i 9780822382874DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223828747 a10.1515/97808223828742doi  a(DE-B1597)552645  a(OCoLC)1226679108  a(OCoLC)1125837403  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJA84.U5bF59 1992 7aPOL0030002bisacsh1 aFlaumenhaft, Harvey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Effective Republic :bAdministration and Constitution in the Thought of Alexander Hamilton /cHarvey Flaumenhaft. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (327 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Principles -- tPart One: Popular Representation -- tII The Characteristic Spirit of Society -- tIII The Natural Rights of Mankind -- tIV The Structural Foundation of Government -- tV The Partition of Power -- tPart Two: Efficacious Administration -- tVI Administrative Efficacy -- tVII Unity -- tVIII Unity and Duration -- tIX Duration -- tX Republican Constitution -- tPart Three: Constitutional Integrity -- tXI Independent Judgment -- tXII Partisanship, Partiality, and Parts of Government -- tXIII Partisanship, Partiality, and Popular Liberty -- tXIV Return to First Principles -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United States has been distinguished among free governments as a "presidential" republic. In The Effective Republic, Harvey Flaumenhaft shows how the study of Alexander Hamilton's political thought opens the way to understanding the nature of this republic and the reasons for its development.Although Hamilton exterted an extraordinary influence on American institutions, his contribution and the thinking behind it often have been obscured and misconstrued by piecemeal approaches to his voluminous writings. Here, Flaumenhaft draws upon more than two dozen volumes of Hamilton's papers to produce a comprehensive account of his thought on the principles of politics-the account which Hamilton himself hoped to give in a multivolume treatise, but died before producing.Beginning with a discussion of the place of general principles in Hamilton's thought, The Effective Republic proceeds to his views on popular representation as a safeguard of individual liberty. Flaumenhaft then elaborates on Hamilton's thinking about efficacious administration, especially how the President and Senate meet the requirements of unity and duration in a republic, and on the importance of an independent judiciary for constitutional integrity. What emerges clearly as Hamilton's chief concern is the need to make government not only safe but effective-hindered from doing harm by its popular base, but also, through the differentiation of administrative powers and tasks, capable of doing good.Interpreting, linking, and, and arranging Hamilton's words, Flaumenhaft allows Hamilton to speak for himself, to explain his benificiaries his vision of what the republican experiment needed in order to succeed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPolitical sciencezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRepublicanismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382874zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382874.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL